00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:20.710
Do you feel that puns are unfair
to those with limited

00:44:20.710 --> 00:44:23.200
language or English as
a second language?

00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:25.060
Is that maybe part
of the reason

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:27.390
they're looked down upon?

00:44:27.390 --> 00:44:29.030
JOHN POLLACK: I think
that puns are good

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:32.530
for learning language.

00:44:32.530 --> 00:44:39.150
And I would say that if you
look at riddles and

00:44:39.150 --> 00:44:43.080
knock-knock jokes, which are
some of the earliest types of

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:46.280
humor that kids learn,
those are almost

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:49.540
always driven by puns.

00:44:49.540 --> 00:44:52.210
In fact, like, what's black and
white and read all over?

00:44:52.210 --> 00:44:52.700
The newspaper.

00:44:52.700 --> 00:44:56.240
That's been bouncing around
since the middle of the 1800s.

00:44:56.240 --> 00:44:59.140
And so I would say
push the puns.

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:00.460
The puns are great.

00:45:00.460 --> 00:45:04.420
